	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>SIDS adopt a strategy for sustainable development</h1>

			
			<h4>
												31 January 2005
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> The 'International meeting to review the implementation of the programme of action for the sustainable development of small island developing states' took place from January 10th - 14th 2005 in Mauritius. It was attended by 18 presidents, vice-presidents and prime ministers, some 60 ministers and nearly 2000 delegates, civil society representatives and journalists from 114 countries, and by 15 UN and other multilateral agencies.</p><p> The major outcomes and proposals of the conference are provided in 'the Mauritius strategy for the further implementation of the programme of action for the sustainable development of SIDS'. This recognises that 'most small-island developing states, as a result of their smallness, persistent structural disadvantages and vulnerabilities, face specific difficulties in integrating into the global economy.' The strategy goes on to reaffirm the commitments of SIDS to the rules-based multilateral trading system. It welcomes the WTO July 2004 package and the new resolve by members to fulfil the development dimension of the Doha Round, and stresses the importance of facilitating effective participation by small economies such as SIDS. The trade section of the 'Mauritius strategy' concludes by listing areas of key concern to SIDS. These are:</p>
<ul>

<li>WTO accession; </li>

<li>graduation from LDC status; </li>

<li>capacity constraints; </li>

<li>technical assistance; </li>

<li>structural vulnerabilities; </li>

<li>erosion of preferences; </li>

<li>structural adjustment; </li>

<li>the relationship between trade, environment and development; </li>

<li>trade and food security; </li>

<li>lack of representation in Geneva.</li>

</ul>
<p> Issues related to the erosion of trade preferences and effects on SIDS were key topics of debate during the conference. Participants also addressed the question of whether a special category for small and vulnerable economies, such as the SIDS, should be established within the WTO system. A number of SIDS pushed for it, while developed countries opposed such a designation, preferring to make commitments to help improve the trade capacities of SIDS.</p><p> The Mauritius strategy elaborates on a wide variety of actions under 20 broad headings, including management of coastal and marine resources and freshwater resources.</p><p> The Commissioner for Development and Humanitarian Affairs said that the EU had a long-standing relationship with SIDS and had joined forces with many of them to meet the challenges facing them. He said that 'Trade and environment, fishery subsidies, affordable medication and improvement in the capacity to negotiate were also areas, as included in the Doha declaration, to which the Union was prepared to assist small-island developing states'.</p><p> The FAO announced on January 17th 2005, that it will convene a special conference in Rome during its governing conference from November 19th to 26th 2005 to review the Mauritius strategy which recommends management that addresses the impact of climate change on food production and the implementation of the FAO code of conduct for responsible fisheries and the FAO high-seas fishing-compliance agreement. The Mauritius strategy also states that sustainable management of ocean resources should promote 'mapping of their exclusive economic zones, monitoring and surveillance of fishing efforts, including appropriate enforcement measures to minimise illegal, unreported and unregulated fishing and over-harvesting'.</p><p> Additionally, the strategy document called on the international community to address issues of special concern to SIDS countries such as trade and food security and improving SPS infrastructure in these countries.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<a href="http://www.un.org/smallislands2005/" target="_self"> <i>Small Islands, Big Stakes,</i> web page</a> </p><p>
<a href="http://www.un.org/News/Press/docs/2005/envdev815.doc.htm" target="_self">UN press release, January 14th 2005</a> </p><p>
<a href="http://www.un.org/News/Press/docs/2005/sag314.doc.htm" target="_self">UN press release January 17th 2005</a> </p><p>
<a href="http://www.ictsd.org/biores/05-01-21/story2.htm" target="_self">ICTSD, <i> BRIDGES, Trade BioRes</i>, Vol. 5, No. 1, January 21st 2005</a> </p><p>

<a href="http://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=12974&amp;Cr=small&amp;Cr1=island" target="_self">UN <i>News Centre</i> preliminary reports ahead of the meeting</a> <br/> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> Under the GATT, an 'enabling clause' was officially adopted that enables the developed country members to give 'differential and more favourable' treatment to developing countries. This provides the legal basis for the GSP, as developed within the framework of UNCTAD and applied to LDCs.</p><p> Within the WTO it has been widely recognised that the exports of developing countries should be given preferential access to developed country markets, and that these concessions do not have to be fully reciprocated. This provides the basis for the 'special and differential treatment' of developing countries that is being called for in several of the negotiating groups on rules, including fisheries subsidies.</p><p> Despite all this recognition, including the provisions of the Doha Declaration that demands that fishery subsidies negotiations should 'take into account the importance of this sector to developing countries' (paragraph 28), no progress has been made to define SDT.</p><p> Another major stumbling block is the lack of any WTO definitions for 'developed' or 'developing countries'. Likewise, there is no special recognition of SIDS within the framework of WTO rules. These omissions need to be rectified if there is to be progress on the agenda of the Mauritius strategy and in order to address the issues raised, such as capacity constraints, technical assistance, structural vulnerabilities, erosion of preferences, and structural adjustment.</p><p> A very important next step therefore is applying the Mauritius strategy to the WTO negotiations on rules (on fisheries subsidies and market access for non-agricultural products). In particular, there is a need to establish SDT for the special case of SIDS in general (market access and fisheries subsidies), and the specific concerns of the small vulnerable coastal states with particular regard to the negotiations of fisheries subsidies.</p>
		</div>
		
